<WRITING SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Constance Smedley: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RSC" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 June 1999</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 December 1999</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily orgName and bibCit cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DRG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 February 2001</DATE><ITEM>converted textual apostrophes and quotation marks to entity references</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SLB" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 November 2002</DATE><ITEM>removed title tag(s) from workscited</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 April 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily PLACE cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 June 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily TGENRENAME cleanup, BIBCIT following P moved before P, BIBCITS TAG added</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>08 April 2005</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: March 2005 Specifications. Mainly tag/attribute name changes</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>2 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>28 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>28 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>2 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>2 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>4 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>7 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>8 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>11 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 February 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>18 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>1 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 March 2011</DATE><ITEM>Cas-ing complete. A few researchnotes to be answered.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>26 April 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>30 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>2 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>10 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb, cft c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>16 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="LSW" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>30 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="ENH" RESP="IMG" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>2 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Smedley, Constance</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P><GENERICRANGE><EXTENTOFOEUVRE>Beginning early in the twentieth century, CS published forty books, about twenty of them <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> and the rest <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">plays</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s books</TGENRE>, and non-fiction including a <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLEMIC">polemical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="FEMINIST">feminist</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="MANIFESTO">manifesto</TGENRE> and a <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">book of memoirs</TGENRE>. Her writing was only one aspect of her career: through her theatrical ideals, <TGENRE GENRENAME="TEXTBOOK">teaching</TGENRE>, and practice (writing and directing plays and <TGENRE GENRENAME="PAGEANT">pageants</TGENRE>, not all of them published)</EXTENTOFOEUVRE></GENERICRANGE> it connected with her work in the visual arts: embroidery, illustration, and social movements.</P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Beginnings</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY>CS was both a writer and a published artist at the age of about sixteen, when she wrote a <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA"><TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">play</TGENRE></TGENRE> for performance at the <ORGNAME>Birmingham School of Art</ORGNAME> and had her first illustration accepted by the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Pall Mall Magazine</TITLE>.</PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY> <PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">It was she who suggested to the authorities that the students should put on a play about <TTHEMETOPIC>art students, their hard work and high ideals</TTHEMETOPIC>. When asked where to find such a play, she volunteered to write it.</PMOTIVES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 9" DBREF="65965">9</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 20-2" DBREF="106055">20-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P> It was called <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Lay Figure</TITLE>, and features a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>serious art student of each gender</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, plus assorted comedy characters drawn from life. The younger students spiritedly refused the demand that their seniors should be allowed to superintend rehearsals; these therefore took place in a spirit of rebellion behind closed doors.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 9" DBREF="65965">9</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 20-2" DBREF="106055">20-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">CS&apos;s father appealed to <NAME>Edgar Pemberton</NAME>, drama critic of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Birmingham Daily Post</TITLE>, for his opinion on this play, and he responded that CS should consider the theatre as a career.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 23" DBREF="106055">23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Early Plays and Journalism</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>CS persevered with writing <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">plays</TGENRE>, and began studying drama and theatre history. One of her early plays, also performed at the <ORGNAME>Birmingham School of Art</ORGNAME>, starred her <NAME STANDARD="Smedley, Ida">sister</NAME>. Another centred on an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">actress</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="reputation, women&apos;s">unjustly seen as scandalous</TMOTIF>, who works incognita as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">governess</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. <TCHARACTERIZATION><PPERFORMANCE>Another, the <TGENRE GENRENAME="ONEACTPLAY">one-act</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs Jordan</TITLE>, was given a skilled amateur production in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Birmingham</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Warwickshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</PPERFORMANCE> The great eighteenth-century actress <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Dorothy Jordan</NAME> was a heroine to CS, because of her breeches roles and her bold and skilful navigation of scandal over her royal lover</TTHEMETOPIC>.</TCHARACTERIZATION> <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>Later Smedley sent <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs Jordan</TITLE> to <NAME STANDARD="Campbell,  Beatrice Stella">Mrs Patrick Campbell</NAME>,</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <PPERFORMANCE>who put it on at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Royalty Theatre,, Soho">Royalty Theatre</ORGNAME> (where it ran for six months as a curtain-raiser to <NAME>Hermann Sudermann</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Magda</TITLE>). <NAME STANDARD="Campbell,  Beatrice Stella">Mrs Campbell</NAME> played the starring role, <RPENALTIES CENSORSHIP="CENSORSHIPYES">after trouble with the censor over its allusions to a member of the royal family behaving badly.</RPENALTIES></PPERFORMANCE> Another play by CS, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">Kitty</TITLE>, had a provincial tour and was later invited to tour <PLACE><GEOG>South Africa</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>, but by that time the manuscript had been lost.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 23, 24, 27, 143" DBREF="106055">23-24, 27, 143</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In her early twenties CS was furiously writing plays for such prominent performers as Mrs Patrick Campbell and <NAME>Violet Vanbrugh</NAME>, <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><PATTITUDES>but was still young enough to take it hard when <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the perpetual change of plans left my plays, so enthusiastically accepted, unproduced.</QUOTE></PATTITUDES></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 28" DBREF="106055">28</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>CS became a <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">journalist</TGENRE> as well as a dramatist. She contributed to<TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Girl&apos;s Realm</TITLE>, edited by <NAME>Violet Alcock</NAME>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 30-1" DBREF="106055">30-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PAUTHORSHIP AUTHORNAMETYPE="PSEUDONYMOUS">and wrote a series of <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">articles</TGENRE> for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">St James&apos;s Gazette</TITLE> under the pseudonym <SOCALLED>the Princess</SOCALLED>, about the issues facing the New Woman.</PAUTHORSHIP></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> In 1903 her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lively journalistic <TGENRE GENRENAME="DIALOGUEORDEBATE">dialogues</TGENRE></QUOTE> written for this paper were collected as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Boudoir Critic</TITLE>, which she calls a novel.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 3" DBREF="66006">3</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 261" DBREF="106055">261</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Damsels in a Woods" DBREF="65947"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PCIRCULATION>This found few readers. CS said that its publishers, <ORGNAME STANDARD="HarperCollins Publishing">Harper&apos;s</ORGNAME>, claimed not to be surprised: they had chosen it to reward merit, not to make a profit.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 47" DBREF="106055">47</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PCIRCULATION></P><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>At the height of the <TTHEMETOPIC>suffrage struggle</TTHEMETOPIC> CS reported militant activities for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Daily Mail</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 146" DBREF="106055">146</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She also sold <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short stories</TGENRE> (as many as she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">could find time to write</QUOTE>) in the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE>, and this brought her the post of European representative on the American <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Everybody&apos;s Magazine</TITLE>. <PEARNINGS>The post carried <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a substantial salary</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 148" DBREF="106055">148</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> that offered her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">genuine independence in the working world.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 149" DBREF="106055">149</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEARNINGS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>In October 1905 the <ORGNAME STANDARD="International Association of Lyceum Clubs" REG="London Lyceum International Club">Lyceum Club</ORGNAME> journal carried an <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">article</TGENRE> by CS entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Stony Path</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 101" DBREF="106055">101</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Here she argued for <TTHEMETOPIC>improvement in the creative conditions faced by British composers</TTHEMETOPIC>: reluctance to perform their works more than once, lack of systems of <TTHEMETOPIC>remuneration</TTHEMETOPIC>, absence of <TTHEMETOPIC>copyright protection</TTHEMETOPIC>, and a system that encouraged performances of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the utterest trash.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 101" DBREF="106055">101</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Novels before the USA</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING>Princesses</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106054" PLACEHOLDER="CS, An April Princess, 1903"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1903-04-10" CERTAINTY="BY">By 10 April 1903</DATE><CHRONPROSE>Playing on her <SOCALLED>Princess</SOCALLED> nickname (dating from her art-student days), and deliberately turning her back on dramatic writing, CS published her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">An April <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Princess</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (10 April 1903): 115" DBREF="54246">(10 April 1903): 115</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="LITERARY">She claimed that its influences included <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Dolly Dialogues</TITLE> by <NAME STANDARD="Hawkins, Sir Anthony Hope">Anthony Hope</NAME>.</PINFLUENCESHER> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>She wrote it during a year at her family&apos;s farmhouse at <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Sheepcote"></PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT>Wooburn Green</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Buckinghamshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>,</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> under its early title of <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="April Princess, An">The Princess Papers</TITLE>, <PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM"><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>and published it chapter by chapter in an amateur magazine for young writers entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Magpie</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 37, 38" DBREF="106055">37, 38</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></PSERIALIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TTONESTYLE>Romantic and part <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiographical</TGENRE>,</TTONESTYLE> this features a heroine who <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lives a fantasy life as a princess. She rules over her own private kingdom of friends, while treating with charming disrespect the <TTHEMETOPIC>rules of society</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 3" DBREF="66006">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Grace Brockington</NAME> writes that this was CS&apos;s most successful novel, showing her as a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rising talent</QUOTE> with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">exuberant intelligence</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 3" DBREF="66006">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Contemporary reviewers hailed it as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one prolonged flash of brilliancy</QUOTE> and as exemplifying <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the champagne of youth, originality, cleverness and self-confidence.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 3" DBREF="66006" QTDIN="QTDINYES">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="ADFEMINAM">The notice in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Birmingham Owl</TITLE> mentioned the local celebrity of CS&apos;s father.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 9" DBREF="106055">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Smedley mentions (as well as praise from various papers including the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Daily News</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Pall Mall Gazette</TITLE>) that this book brought her attention and commissions for writing from <NAME>Robert Barr</NAME>, editor of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Idler, The">The Idler</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 39-40" DBREF="106055">39-40</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Praise for it from various distinguished names was mingled with delight in Smedley&apos;s <SOCALLED>princess</SOCALLED> persona <RSELFDESCRIPTION>She later wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Looking back, I see I remained an incorrigible amateur long after I should have put away school-girl visions.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 46" DBREF="106055">46</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">An April Princess</TITLE> gave rise to two more princess novels and various <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">journalistic</TGENRE> writing. <NAME>Robert Barr</NAME> handed over to CS, for three months, his own column called <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">The Idler&apos;s Club</TITLE>, and he published in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Idler, The">The Idler</TITLE> eight of her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><SIC>very unique</SIC> <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE></QUOTE> under the title <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">The Diversions of a Princess</TITLE>. <PAUTHORSHIP AUTHORNAMETYPE="ANONYMOUS">The first of her series of <TGENRE GENRENAME="DIALOGUEORDEBATE">dialogues</TGENRE> between the princess as <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>modern young woman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and her <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Victorian aunt</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> appeared anonymously in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">St James&apos;s Gazette</TITLE>.</PAUTHORSHIP> This gave her the entree into the editorial offices of that paper, and an invitation to write a daily column for it on any topic she liked (a freedom which at first she found paralysing).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 40, 48, 50" DBREF="106055">40, 48, 50</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This first dialogue concerned the <TTHEMETOPIC>Baconian controversy</TTHEMETOPIC>. CS&apos;s father was given to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">harping</QUOTE> on his belief that <NAME STANDARD="Bacon, Francis,, 1561 - 1626">Sir Francis Bacon</NAME> wrote the works of <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME>. This is the position taken by Smedley&apos;s Victorian aunt, while the niece opposes it.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 48" DBREF="106055">48</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="ADFEMINAM">Smedley&apos;s <NAME STANDARD="Smedley, William Thomas">father</NAME> recognized her hand in this essay when he read it at his club, but his <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">genial good humour</QUOTE> ensured that he was amused rather than angry.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 48" DBREF="106055">48</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66008" PLACEHOLDER="CS, The June Princess, 1909"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1909-02-18" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid February 1909</DATE><CHRONPROSE>Having marked the beginning of her <ORGNAME STANDARD="International Association of Lyceum Clubs" REG="London Lyceum International Club">Lyceum Club</ORGNAME> work with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">An April Princess</TITLE>, CS marked its ending with another <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The June Princess</TITLE>, a sober meditation on the experience of <TTHEMETOPIC>public life</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (18 February 1909): 575" DBREF="54246">(18 February 1909): 57</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 3" DBREF="66006">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONPROSE></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The June Princess</TITLE> opens with the protagonist <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">slaving away</QUOTE> at running a <TTHEMETOPIC>club</TTHEMETOPIC> which, she insists, is intended not for the benefit of its members alone but <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">for <TTHEMETOPIC>Internationalism</TTHEMETOPIC> . . . . You see, it is such a sensible and beautiful idea to bind the world together.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 6" DBREF="66006" QTDIN="QTDINYES">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Many of her opinions are those of CS herself: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the different forms of Arts must be the surest links to bind the world together, because <TTHEMETOPIC>Art</TTHEMETOPIC> holds universal understanding.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 8" DBREF="66006" QTDIN="QTDINYES">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Hers, too, is her princess&apos;s mood at the end of the novel, a desire to <TTHEMETOPIC>escape from responsibility </TTHEMETOPIC>and from the prison of the organization, back to the freedom of being a private person.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 11" DBREF="66006">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Between CS&apos;s two princess novels two others intervened: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="For Heart-o-Gold">For Heart-o-Gold. A <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">Romantic</TGENRE> Novel</TITLE> in 1904, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Conflict</TITLE> in 1907.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>She wrote later of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="For Heart-o-Gold">For Heart-o-Gold</TITLE> in terms of a <TGENRE GENRENAME="FABLE">fable</TGENRE>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a grown-up version of the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">Princess</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Swineherd</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <PDEDICATION>dedicated to the <TCHARACTERIZATION><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">Jester</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, who formed the hero, and who was a picture of <NAME>James Welch</NAME>.</TCHARACTERIZATION></PDEDICATION></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 47" DBREF="106055">47</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><TTONESTYLE><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Feminist Companion to Literature in English: Women Writers from the Middle Ages to the Present, The">The Feminist Companion</TITLE> calls CS&apos;s novels in general <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">romantic, though not cloyingly sentimental.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTONESTYLE></RRESPONSES> <PEDITIONS><PCIRCULATION>Recent reprints on demand suggest that others too see them as romantic.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PCIRCULATION></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Conflict</TITLE> and more</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66007" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Conflict, 1907"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1907-03-08" CERTAINTY="BY">By early March 1907</DATE><CHRONPROSE>In her <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Conflict</TITLE>, CS issued her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">first serious <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE></QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 52" DBREF="106055">52</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> about <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the <TTHEMETOPIC>unsheltered lives of working women</TTHEMETOPIC></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe" DBREF="65947"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> (that is, <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">middle-class women pursuing careers in business</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (8 March 1907): 79" DBREF="54246">(8 March 1907): 79</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 10" DBREF="65965">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The author later wrote that this book sprang from her inner <TTHEMETOPIC>conflict between the values</TTHEMETOPIC> of the <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> artistic world</TTHEMETOPIC> (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the golden world of woman&apos;s sheltered graciousness, of romantic and enthusiastic friendships</QUOTE> pursued on a purely personal basis), and the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Birmingham</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Warwickshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> values of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTHEMETOPIC>responsibility for the common good</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE> It sprang, too, from her first-ever contact with the kind of working women she met through the <ORGNAME>Writers&apos; Club</ORGNAME>. She followed this with another novel, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Daughter</TITLE>, 1908.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 52" DBREF="106055">52</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The heroine of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Conflict</TITLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Mary Ellestree</TCHARACTERNAME>, is a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">prototype of the modern business girl</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 52" DBREF="106055">52</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> who embodies <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an entirely <TTHEMETOPIC>new concept of femininity</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 53" DBREF="106055">53</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Reviews were good in both England and the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE> for <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">this austere novel</QUOTE> (as the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> called it), and its heroine was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">welcomed as a new type in fiction.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 52" DBREF="106055" QTDIN="QTDINYES">52</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>A Trilogy</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>CS then began to publish what she called <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a group of three Family Pictures, treating . . . of the relations of husband and wife</QUOTE> or on issues confronting the <TTHEMETOPIC>contemporary family</TTHEMETOPIC>:<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Commoners vii" DBREF="67368">vii</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Service">Service. A <TGENRE GENRENAME="DOMESTIC">Domestic</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">Novel</TGENRE></TITLE>, 1910, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mothers and Fathers</TITLE>, 1911, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Commoners&apos; Rights</TITLE>, 1912. <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>Her husband provided frontispieces for these books.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Service</TITLE>, the first in the series, sets out to show the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">love of Righteousness</QUOTE> (or, one might say, of public spirit) planted <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">like a tiny seed in the heart of a family</QUOTE> which at first sight appears limited to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the love of one another and of material ambitions.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Commoners ix" DBREF="67368">ix</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Evening Standard</TITLE> found this novel fresh and compelling, and its characters of the five women in the Sturge family <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">little masterpieces of understanding and delineation.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Commoners prelims" DBREF="67368">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66046" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Mothers and Fathers, 1911"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1911-02-21" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid February 1911</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP>Under her married name of <SOCALLED>Constance Smedley Armfield</SOCALLED>, CS published a determinedly progressivist <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mothers and Fathers</TITLE>. In the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE> it was titled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Mothers and Fathers">The Larger Growth (Mothers and Fathers)</TITLE>.</PAUTHORSHIP></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (17 February 1911): 61" DBREF="54246">(17 February 1911): 61</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The American title echoes <NAME STANDARD="Dryden, John">Dryden</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">All for Love</TITLE> (Act 4, scene 1): <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Men are but children of a larger growth.</QUOTE></TINTERTEXTUALITY> <PDEDICATION>The book is dedicated <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">To Another Father and Mother in gratitude for a wide outlook.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth prelims" DBREF="65886">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> These dedicatees may well be her own parents, thus marked as different from those in the novel.</PDEDICATION> <PARCHIVALLOCATION>The copy of the US edition now at the <ORGNAME>University of Alberta</ORGNAME> was inscribed by the author to <NAME>Mary E. Woolley</NAME> (who is listed on the provisional committee for the American Lyceum).<SCHOLARNOTE><P>Orlando is grateful to <NAME>Kate Lane-Smith</NAME> and <NAME>Liam Farrer</NAME> for deciphering the name.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></PARCHIVALLOCATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This is a powerful depiction of the <TTHEMETOPIC>oppressiveness of family life</TTHEMETOPIC>, especially for the central figure, <TCHARACTERNAME>Jessica Maddox</TCHARACTERNAME>; yet it ends with Jessica reconciled to the family life which she used to loath, and working in the <TTHEMETOPIC>domestic arts</TTHEMETOPIC> which she once despised. And the family, still loving, is no longer anxious, constricting and devouring, but now (like the book itself) forward-looking and optimistic. The introduction sets out its message: that parents <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">must respect their children as individuals</QUOTE> and that <TTHEMETOPIC>reforms</TTHEMETOPIC> are necessary to free the world from tyranny. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">CS sets her story in a commonplace household,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth vii" DBREF="65886">vii</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE> because she believes <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">that though people live small lives in a small way, their feelings are no less poignant in that they are compressed.</QUOTE> She also believes in progress: which, heralded by <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the bicycle . . . the forerunner of the run-about</QUOTE> or small car,  ensures that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">into the most shut-in families, the breath of a wider hope and a more free air is coming.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth viii" DBREF="65886">viii</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>The child Jessica can hardly bear her parents&apos; (really her father&apos;s) refusal to let the children accept the invitation of new neighbours to play next door, instead of walking with him as they always do on Saturdays. The parents do not in fact refuse, but resort to what today would be called <TTHEMETOPIC>passive aggression</TTHEMETOPIC>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">You did n&apos;t want to leave your poor papa alone on his only holiday?</QUOTE> cries their mother, while their father says: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">If my company is n&apos;t felt to be a privilege, I &apos;ve no desire to waste it on them; none. It &apos;s just as well that they should realise what it means to give up all my Saturdays, when other men are occupying themselves with selfish pleasures.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth 8" DBREF="65886">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Jessica, who has the temerity to suggest that they might walk with their father <EMPH>and</EMPH> visit the neighbours, then suffers <TTHEMETOPIC>agonies of guilt</TTHEMETOPIC>, only alleviated after she gets lost, drenched in a storm, found by her father, and fussed over (both parents being constantly in a state of fear for their children) in the belief that she might get rheumatic fever. Personal feelings are never mentioned in this family, so nobody knows <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the children&apos;s feelings to their parents; how they pitied and loved and patronised the mother . . . who . . . was so indefinite a personality beside the vivid positive superiority of <QUOTE DIRECT="N">papa</QUOTE>,</QUOTE> who goes out to work and carries responsibility for the whole family.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth 11" DBREF="65886">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">Jessica and her younger brother, Edgar, both respond with ecstasy to an offer to borrow books they have not already read (<NAME>William Morris</NAME>, <NAME>William Blake</NAME>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[a]nd people I don&apos;t know; and books on <TTHEMETOPIC>Socialism</TTHEMETOPIC></QUOTE>);</TINTERTEXTUALITY> Jessica scans the bookshelves with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">gasps and croons of uncontrollable delight.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth 117" DBREF="65886">117</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rights of women">When she confides to Edgar that it is terrible to be a girl, he answers seriously (as if the concept of <TTHEMETOPIC>surplus women</TTHEMETOPIC> were obvious even to a child): <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Yes, I suppose it is . . . . I wonder why so many more than are wanted come into the world?</QUOTE> To which Jessica replies that even the wanted ones are wanted only as animals, or more properly as keepers to tend the comforts of the animals who are men.</TMOTIF><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth 112" DBREF="65886">112</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>The book charts the gradual, up-and-down, always painful but inexorable <TTHEMETOPIC>self-emancipation of these children</TTHEMETOPIC>. Even the naturally conformist Catharine, still living with her parents at the end of the book, is by then much involved, with her mother, in <TTHEMETOPIC>local affairs like politics and setting up a new library</TTHEMETOPIC>. When the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>eldest, serious, intelligent, ambitious Charles, a patriarch in the making</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, first announces his intention of leaving home and his father&apos;s office to work in London, his parents are stricken. His mother says to him: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Oh dear, when I think of you as a little child . . . . Our little boy! You did love us then&mdash;.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth 96" DBREF="65886">96</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Charles, however, does well in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, and a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">bequest from a man whose <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rescue">son he saved from an accident</TMOTIF> gives him money</TMOTIF>. He almost <TTHEMETOPIC>stands for parliament, as a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Conservative Party">Conservative</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, before he realises the gulf between his own Conservativism (believing in moderate progress, though not of course in women going out to work) and the views of the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>rural Tories</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who would be his constituents. These Tories include the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>land-owning</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Lacy family, by whom he has previously been dazzled. At the end of the story, at forty, he is <TTHEMETOPIC>elected, but as a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Liberal Party">Liberal</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, and he loves and marries not <TCHARACTERNAME>Lettice Lacy</TCHARACTERNAME> whom he first loved but <TCHARACTERNAME>Isadora Bent</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>self-educated woman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who used to sell books in her father&apos;s shop and is now a keen Liberal worker. Each stage of Charles&apos;s development causes intense anxiety to his parents, to whom Isadora&apos;s lower and Lettice&apos;s higher social status make them equally objects of suspicion. Worse than this, Isadora shared a boy-and-girl love with the younger Edgar, and the Maddoxes have ruthlessly broken up the engagement. Her acceptance into the family shows how far even the Maddox parents have progressed.</P><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">Of the younger children, Edgar the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>dreamer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> begins his growth towards <TTHEMETOPIC>intellectual independence</TTHEMETOPIC> when his parents unwillingly permit him to travel to <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE> with friends. In Italy he falls in love with Margaret Cheney.</TSETTINGPLACE> They make a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>reformist, socially conscious couple</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, full of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTHEMETOPIC>theories for the practical betterment</TTHEMETOPIC> of things and people.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth 212" DBREF="65886">212</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Jessica, in whom the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="work for a living">desire to work becomes a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">monomania</QUOTE></TMOTIF>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Larger Growth 177" DBREF="65886">177</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> is permitted two years at a domestic college and becomes a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">professional housekeeper</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. In practice she hates much of her work, yet she is persuaded by <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>unconventional friends</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> to see her role as a reformer of home life, helping others towards personal freedom. By the end of the book she is helping to run a <TTHEMETOPIC>hostel for students</TTHEMETOPIC>. There is irony in the destiny of each Maddox child: Charles the boy patriarch has become a Liberal, Edgar the dreamer a civic planner, the conventional Catharine a force for change, and Jessica, whose bugbear was domesticity, is making that her profession.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times">The Times</TITLE> noted with approval that the book was well-balanced, evincing sympathy for both sides of its private-public struggle, and pleasurable as well as thought-provoking.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Commoners prelims" DBREF="67368">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>William Dean Howells</NAME>, an admirer of CS, hailed this novel (together with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Service. A Domestic Novel">Service</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Commoners&apos; Rights</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Una and the Lions</TITLE>) in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">North American Review</TITLE> under the title <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Intensive School of Literature</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 216" DBREF="106055">216</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67368" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Commoners&apos; Rights, 1912"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="IDENTIFIABLE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><NAME>Maxwell Armfield</NAME>&apos;s frontispiece to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Commoners&apos; Rights"><TTHEMETOPIC>Commoners&apos; Rights</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, 1912, shows <SOCALLED>Chippingdun</SOCALLED>, the book&apos;s fictional version of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Minchinhampton">Minchinhampton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. His later illustrations also show the town or its beautiful surroundings.</TSETTINGPLACE></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS> <PDEDICATION>The work is dedicated to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Our Friends in the <PLACE><REGION>Cotswolds</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Commoners prelims" DBREF="67368">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION> and the preface mentions with respect the work of the <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME>National Trust</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Commoners ix" DBREF="67368">ix</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Commoners&apos; Rights">Commoners&apos; Rights</TITLE> is a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">record of the warfare that started up and raged about <PLACE><PLACENAME>Minchinhampton Common</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Minchinhampton"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, ending in its ultimate <TTHEMETOPIC>purchase by the Nation</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE> The cause of the commoners, first taken up by the <TTHEMETOPIC>Radicals</TTHEMETOPIC>, became in the end a cause supported by the <TTHEMETOPIC>local <ORGNAME>Conservative Party</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 201" DBREF="106055">201</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Along with this CS traces the growth of the individual soul within marriage, expressing the hope that husbands and wives will come to be judged, like single people, for their relations to other people and society as well as to their partners. She depicts the love of righteousness first in retreat and then expanding, and a wife and husband building their happy union and interacting for good with the world beyond them.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>More Early Novels</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Other <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> that CS produced almost concurrently with her trilogy were <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Emotions of Martha</TITLE>, 1911 (issued through the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Bodleian Library">Religious Tract Society</ORGNAME> and dedicated to <NAME>Margaret Armfield</NAME>), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ruth&apos;s Marriage</TITLE>, 1912 (also through  the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Bodleian Library">Religious Tract Society</ORGNAME>), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">New Wine and Old Bottles</TITLE> (<ORGNAME>T. Fisher Unwin</ORGNAME>, 1913), and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Una and the Lions</TITLE> (<ORGNAME>Chatto and Windus</ORGNAME>, 1914).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Emotions of Martha</TITLE> is a <TGENRE GENRENAME="RELIGIOUS">religious</TGENRE> novel, in that <TCHARACTERNAME>Martha Spence</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>spiritual and emotional development</TTHEMETOPIC> run side by side. At the outset she feels certain that she has a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">remarkable artistic talent</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> (her subjects being mostly literary and melodramatic) and wants to escape the narrowness of her family, especially her <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>good, selfless sister</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and go to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> to study. Before she leaves she has already met and begun to admire <TCHARACTERNAME>Michael Keene</TCHARACTERNAME>, a more experienced artist whose parents are <ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Friends" REG="Quakers">Friends or Quakers</ORGNAME>. Martha ends by giving up her ambitions, ceasing to despise <TTHEMETOPIC>housework</TTHEMETOPIC>, and <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="marriage ending">turning eagerly to marriage</TMOTIF> with Michael. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">Both of them quote the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REND="normal">Bible</TITLE> a great deal as they declare their love,</TINTERTEXTUALITY> but Michael does allow that a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="work for a living">woman may earn her living in London</TMOTIF> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">and be splendidly useful,</QUOTE> and that Martha must not <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">condemn the entire Art world or working-women&apos;s world by the few people you knew.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Martha 313" DBREF="67369">313</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">On the Fighting Line</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66025" PLACEHOLDER="CS, On the Fighting Line, 1915"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1915-03-04" CERTAINTY="BY">By March 1915</DATE><CHRONPROSE>In another <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">On the Fighting Line</TITLE>, CS <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">explore[d] the problems of <TTHEMETOPIC>gender stereotype</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (4 March 1915): 79" DBREF="54246">(4 March 1915): 79</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 4" DBREF="66006">4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Her protagonist, <TCHARACTERNAME>Minnie Blunt</TCHARACTERNAME>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">scrapes a menial living as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">secretary</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>,</QUOTE> yet <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="work for a living">feels passionately idealistic about her work</TMOTIF> and romantic about her <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>employer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, Mr Richard, and about <SOCALLED>real men</SOCALLED> in general. Unfortunately these two ideals prove incompatible. Her business environment is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">closely connected with the spread of <TTHEMETOPIC>Imperialism</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 224" DBREF="106055">224</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 4" DBREF="66006">4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> When Mr Richard takes an interest in her and a relationship develops, he spoils their <TTHEMETOPIC>first kiss</TTHEMETOPIC> by saying (as she puts it later in her diary), <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">he hates women to be unwomanly and he will have to kiss all the hardness in me away.</QUOTE> Although she conventionally accepts that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">true men give women everything and work for them,</QUOTE> she feels diminished by his offer to support her and thus make her dependent.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 4-5" DBREF="66006" QTDIN="QTDINYES">4-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She realises at last that what she wants is not a <SOCALLED>real man</SOCALLED> (still less the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>imperialist heroes</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> she has formerly admired),<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 9-10" DBREF="66006">9-10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> but the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">man next door, Jack, a writer, a male suffragist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and an enemy to the conventional <TTHEMETOPIC>concept of gendered spheres</TTHEMETOPIC>. Jack is in fact the one man with whom <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTHEMETOPIC>marriage</TTHEMETOPIC> wouldn&apos;t be a perpetual strain, but just a happy, interesting companionship.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 5" DBREF="66006" QTDIN="QTDINYES">5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Redwing</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67367" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Redwing, 1916"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1916-12-15" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid December 1916</DATE><CHRONPROSE>CS published another <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Redwing</TITLE> (which she had intended to call <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Redwing">The People Mimsy Knew</TITLE>).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Redwing 6" DBREF="67367">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Dated from the <ORGNAME>Bodleian Library</ORGNAME> acquisition stamp.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Another novel by CS, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Justice Walk</TITLE>, written in the first year of the war but unpublished until 1924, deals, like <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">On the Fighting Line</TITLE>, with her <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLITICALWRITING">political beliefs</TGENRE>. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Justice Walk</TITLE> concerns the <TTHEMETOPIC>place of art in national life</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 224-225" DBREF="106055">224-225</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>A first chapter of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Redwing</TITLE>, a kind of prologue, presents <TCHARACTERNAME>Mimsy Holman</TCHARACTERNAME> at school, sitting like a trapped rabbit in the sanctum of the headmistress, while her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">face, convulsed and white, discharged moisture at every aperture.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Redwing 8" DBREF="67367">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She is accused of the <TTHEMETOPIC>crime of intention to cheat</TTHEMETOPIC>, since she copied out a complex problem from <NAME>Euclid</NAME> and kept a record of it on her blotting-paper. In fact, when none of her class could solve the problem, she had worked on it at home until, after copying it on the blotting-paper, she found she could solve it. She never meant to cheat and suffers agonies when accused, but <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="reputation, women&apos;s">after this loss of her character she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">entered on a future dark with fear</QUOTE> and shame, at the school which she used to love</TMOTIF>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Redwing 14" DBREF="67367">14</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> CS suggests, however, that the experience shapes Mimsy for good, making her compassionate and ready to believe that sinners need only a chance in order to do better.</P><P>We next meet Mimsy at fifteen, staying with a richer family friend, <TCHARACTERNAME>Vivace Heston</TCHARACTERNAME>, and finding it exhausting to pretend she sees the <TTHEMETOPIC>moneyed life of leisure</TTHEMETOPIC> as natural. At not quite seventeen, pretending to be twenty, she is so unhappy at home that she becomes a kind of governess to Redwing (now <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Navarro, Redwing">Redwing Neville</TCHARACTERNAME>, since the family changed its name from Navarro), a strong, mature-looking boy only three years younger than herself, whose father has recently had a breakdown and whose mother finds him <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">unmanageable . . . a nuisance; a great nuisance.</QUOTE> Mimsy cannot imagine herself teaching him anything.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Redwing 67" DBREF="67367">67</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In the end they learn together; she feels like a bullied elder sister, and she comes to love him. Soon they learn the family <TMOTIF>secret</TMOTIF>: that Redwing&apos;s father has been in <TTHEMETOPIC>prison for obtaining money on false pretences</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Redwing 104" DBREF="67367">104</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Mimsy is dismissed, but the family continues to recur in her life, while she pities their outcast status, and silently loves Redwing&mdash;even when she becomes involved with the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>heroic explorer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Franklin Scott</TCHARACTERNAME>, whose fortune is bound up with that of Redwing&apos;s family. Scott is an ideal to Mimsy and was a friend to the elder Navarro , but a friend who betrayed him over their business dealings, which had to do with <TTHEMETOPIC>mining gold in Africa</TTHEMETOPIC>. Redwing hates and condemns both her and Scott&mdash;until the final eclaircissement when Mimsy and Redwing declare their love. Although his declaration includes <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I can&apos;t feel the sort of thing most men feel; I hate most women,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Redwing 315" DBREF="67367">315</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> they have the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="happy ending">prospect</TMOTIF> of independence at a ranch near <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Monterey</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="California"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, and just enough money to make a go of it.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Short Fiction</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE"><DATE>November 1911</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION><TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Craftsman</TITLE>, volume 21, carried CS&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Turnip Top,&apos; A <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">Story</TGENRE></TITLE>, published under her married name as <SOCALLED>Constance Smedley Armfield</SOCALLED>, on pages 147-151.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 14n31" DBREF="65965">14n31</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67366" PLACEHOLDER="CS, The Fruit of her Hands, 1915"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1915-05-15" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid May 1915</DATE><CHRONPROSE>In a 32-page <TGENRE GENRENAME="TRACTPAMPHLET"><TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">pamphlet</TGENRE></TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fruit of her Hands</TITLE>, CS set out to persuade women in particular <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLITICALWRITING">to challenge the political attitudes and habits</TGENRE> that lead to <TTHEMETOPIC>war</TTHEMETOPIC>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Fruit prelims" DBREF="67366">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="IDENTIFIABLE" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS"><TCHARACTERNAME>Mrs Hodgkinson</TCHARACTERNAME>, a widow recently settled in the little country town of Chippenden and expecting her son George to join her on his leave from the army, is obsessed with social status and class.</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE> It is her guilty secret that her husband was in trade; she strives to run an elegant household with minimum expenditure, and cultivates not the next-door neighbours (who also have trade connections and have started a Boys&apos; Club at which classes mingle) but those with status in the community, who will be able to offer George tennis and <TTHEMETOPIC>shooting</TTHEMETOPIC> when he comes home. She finds it hard to deal with the Vicar, whose views are suspect (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Taking your brother&apos;s life is <TMOTIF>murder</TMOTIF>, and not all the flags and speeches in the world can make it Christian</QUOTE>),<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Fruit 18" DBREF="67366">18</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> but whom she cannot afford to make an enemy of.</P><P>George does not come home, but dies in the trenches. Mrs Hodgkinson begins to hate the patriotic rhetoric people use in proffering sympathy, their remarks about giving the last drop of our blood. In fashionable society where the men have been out shooting, she realises that <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">some men enjoy destruction</TMOTIF>. By the end of the story she has joined her once-despised next-door neighbour in trying to influence the next generation, in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the warfare against war.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Fruit 32" DBREF="67366">32</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>In another 32-page pamphlet, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Ways of her Household</TITLE> (published without a date and variously listed as 1914 or 1915), CS tells another little <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">moral story</TGENRE> against the <TOPIC STANDARD="World War One">war</TOPIC>. Her protagonist, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Smith, Lottie">Lottie Smith <FOREIGN REG="born" LANG="fr">n&eacute;e</FOREIGN> Riepenhausen</TCHARACTERNAME>, has worked in England as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>German governess</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and married an Englishman, and has a son, John, just the same age as her brother&apos;s German son, Franz. The story can almost be guessed from this beginning. <TPLOT>By its end, Franz has given his life for Germany and John is preparing to <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">shell and burn his mother&apos;s birthplace</TMOTIF>.</TPLOT> Details reflect CS&apos;s individual ideas: on a visit to England before the war, Franz upsets his aunt by crushing a bee under his boot (as, she thinks, her husband or son would not have done); and at the end of the story Lottie has suddenly realised how nurseries are full of <TTHEMETOPIC>toy guns and toy soldiers</TTHEMETOPIC>, and sees a way for women, mothers, to help to bring peace.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Earlier Children&apos;s Books</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>1905</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES"><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>Having already written <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s stories</TGENRE> for magazines,</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> CS enlisted her former teacher <NAME>Louisa Agnes Talbot</NAME> as collaborator on a <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s novel</TGENRE> called <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Wizards</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> of Ryetown</TITLE>,</PAUTHORSHIP> <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>with illustrations by her former fellow-student <NAME>Angusine Macgregor</NAME>.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Sylvia&apos;s Travels</TITLE>, 1911, another <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s book</TGENRE>, <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>illustrated by her <NAME STANDARD="Armfield, Maxwell">husband</NAME></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS> <PDEDICATION>and dedicated to <NAME>Mimi Clementi</NAME>,</PDEDICATION> was Smedley&apos;s own favourite.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 216" DBREF="106055">216</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Sylvia prelims" DBREF="67247">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Sylvia is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">woodcutter&apos;s daughter</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and such a good little girl that her father can safely leave her alone in their hut in the forest, mending his shirt and feeding herself with homemade vegetable soup from the garden, while he goes to visit the city. <TPLOT>Sylvia is persuaded by a <TTHEMETOPIC>magic bird with human speech</TTHEMETOPIC> to visit the world, and her travels become a <TMOTIF>quest</TMOTIF> to help the king and queen and <TCHARACTERNAME>Princess Hildur</TCHARACTERNAME> (who has abandoned her parents and retreated to a tower to grow her hair) by ridding them of the evil power of the <TTHEMETOPIC>Hobby Beasts</TTHEMETOPIC>. These beasts, who are terrorising humans and animals alike, are impossible to conquer (as Sylvia&apos;s two male companions attempt to do), but Sylvia masters them by love and truth.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Striking a Blow for Feminism</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>CS <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">reported</TGENRE> for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Daily Mail</TITLE> on various <TTHEMETOPIC>suffragette activities (a procession to the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Albert Hall</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and an occasion when women chained themselves to the railings in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Parliament Yard</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>)</TTHEMETOPIC>. She reported the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTHEMETOPIC>sex-hatred</TTHEMETOPIC></QUOTE> of the crowds, the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">howls and <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">blows</TMOTIF> and bestial faces</QUOTE> and on the other side the <TTHEMETOPIC>courage of the women</TTHEMETOPIC>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a positive light seemed to emanate from them, a stillness, a repose, even happiness</QUOTE> with no trace of either fear or excitement.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 146" DBREF="106055">146</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106057" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman! A Few Shrieks, 1907"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1907-01-" CERTAINTY="AFTER">1907</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP AUTHORNAMETYPE="ANONYMOUS">An <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">extravagant <TGENRE GENRENAME="FEMINIST">feminist</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLEMIC">polemic</TGENRE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 3" DBREF="66006">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> by CS appeared anonymously (by <SOCALLED>X</SOCALLED>) under the self-mocking title of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Woman: A Few Shrieks!</TITLE>.</PAUTHORSHIP></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 147" DBREF="106055">147</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>An appendix, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Women and the State</TITLE> by <NAME>Ethel Snowden</NAME>, was reprinted from the January number of <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The World&apos;s Work</TITLE>, giving a brief history of women in local government and public positions.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 121ff" DBREF="106057">121ff</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PDEDICATION>The book is dedicated to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">those women on the fighting line who have had the courage to face ridicule, and the wit to turn the laugh upon their enemies by their indifference to derision.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman prelims" DBREF="106057">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION><PADVERTISING>A page at the back advertises the book&apos;s publisher, the <ORGNAME>Garden City Press</ORGNAME>, for high quality, low prices, and the fact that all adult employees are also shareholders.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Women" DBREF="106057">back page</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PADVERTISING> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="MISQUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="FEMALE">Its title plays on an infamous and popular phrase apparently coined by <NAME>Eliza Lynn Linton</NAME>: <SOCALLED>the shrieking sisterhood.</SOCALLED></TINTERTEXTUALITY> The <ORGNAME>British Library</ORGNAME> catalogue lists this book with a longer title: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Woman: A Few Shrieks!">Woman: A Few Shrieks! Setting forth the necessity of shrieking till the shrieks be heard</TITLE>. <PEDITIONS>It had a new edition (again with the shorter title) at London in 1908.</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It hammers home its message with typographical contrast: running heads in archaic black-letter; subheadings and opprobrious epithets in heavy bold type.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This book, with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">intentional impertinence</QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 147" DBREF="106055">147</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> decries the traditional view of separate gendered spheres as applicable only in a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">toy-box world</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 8" DBREF="106057">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It emphasizes women&apos;s need for routes, no matter how difficult, to economic independence. Each of Smedley&apos;s propositions, or <SOCALLED>shrieks</SOCALLED>, is countered by brickbats which she represents as lobbed by <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Old-Fashioned People</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 5-6" DBREF="106057">5-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Such people are redefined as the work unfolds as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Stereotyped Opposers</QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 8" DBREF="106057">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Mediaeval Left-overs</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Prehistoric Throw-backs</QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 9" DBREF="106057">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Stay-as-you-were Evangelists</QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 10" DBREF="106057">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Fossil-diggers</QUOTE>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Glass-cased Relics</QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 19" DBREF="106057">19</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and other epithets. Smedley dismantles a clutch of received opinions: for instance, that both sexes are happy with woman&apos;s place being in the home (protected and supported by man, and ministering to his needs), that men are charmed by submissive women and avoid active and independent women, and so on. She demonstrates how gender influences people&apos;s views of others&apos; actions by printing the report of an unseemly fracas in parliament and then substituting female for male names.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 38-9" DBREF="106057">38-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>After her Shrieks come six <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Open Letters</TITLE>, addressing various specimens of anti-suffragist manhood: a Tory landowner MP (named John Bull after the national symbol), a professor, a typical young man (Smith of Surbiton), a man of the world (the last a non-English character, the only one known by what seems to be a concealed actual name, Count K&mdash;). Another letter addresses anti-suffrage MPs, and another a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Tea-and-Tennis girl</QUOTE> named Ethel,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 94" DBREF="106057">94</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> one of those <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">real old-fashioned frivolous girls</QUOTE> who <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">look up to men and are ready to obey them, and think they are much, much, much the superior being.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CS, Woman 95" DBREF="106057">95</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">CS found that while the militant suffragettes welcomed this book as likely to advance their aims, other parts of the movement whom she calls the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Old Guard</QUOTE> disliked the word <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">shrieks</QUOTE> and the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">undignified</QUOTE> and unladlylike language applied to men. CS found it no fun to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fastidiously</QUOTE> dismissed by those she considered allies.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 147" DBREF="106055">147</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Grace Brockington</NAME> particularly recommends this among CS&apos;s works.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 3" DBREF="66006">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RSELFDESCRIPTION>CS classified this book, with two later titles, as <TGENRE GENRENAME="SOCIALSCIENCE">sociology</TGENRE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 261" DBREF="106055">261</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Flowers and Animals</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66205" PLACEHOLDER="CS and Maxwell Armfield, The Flower Book, 1910"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE" CHRONCOLUMN1="WRITINGCLIMATE1" RELEVANCE1="DECADE1"><DATE VALUE="1910-10-13" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-October 1910</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES"><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>CS (as <SOCALLED>Constance Armfield</SOCALLED>) and her husband, <NAME>Maxwell Armfield</NAME>, published the first of their written-and-illustrated collaborations, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Flower Book</TITLE>.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></PAUTHORSHIP></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (13 October 1910): 378" DBREF="54246">(13 October 1910): 378</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Armfield" DBREF="29268">under Armfield</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>She supplied the text, writing one story every morning when she first lived at <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="The Uplands"></PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT>Minchinhampton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>,</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> and he the illustrations, using flowers from their Cotswold garden. <PDEDICATION>The book was dedicated to <NAME>Jessie Horncastle</NAME>.</PDEDICATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 194" DBREF="106055">194</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 12" DBREF="65965">12</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Flower Book prelims" DBREF="66205">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Its contents are sorted into several groups: <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The <TTHEMETOPIC>Meadows</TTHEMETOPIC> and Coppice</TITLE> (containing, for instance, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Grass</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC"><TTHEMETOPIC>Snowdrops</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC"><TTHEMETOPIC>Harebells</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>), <TTHEMETOPIC><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Hedge</TITLE> (covering blackthorn, elder, briar, and honeysuckle)</TTHEMETOPIC>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The <TTHEMETOPIC>Garden</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Pool</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The <TTHEMETOPIC>Herb</TTHEMETOPIC> Patch</TITLE>. The tone runs to whimsy. The snowdrops, for instance, engage in <TGENRE GENRENAME="DIALOGUEORDEBATE">dialogue</TGENRE> with other plants which treat them like naughty children for their desire to open while the world is still cold and asleep. <TTHEMETOPIC>Violets</TTHEMETOPIC> declare: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">There is no death.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Flower Book, vii-viii, 8, 12" DBREF="66205">vii-viii, 8, 12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66206" PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, The Armfields&apos; Animal-Book, 1922"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1922-11-16" CERTAINTY="BY">By 16 November 1922</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES"><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>A dozen years after <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Flower Book</TITLE>, CS and her <NAME STANDARD="Armfield, Maxwell">husband</NAME> did a similar collaboration (her words, his pictures) in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Armfields&apos; Animal-Book</TITLE>, 1922 (she as <SOCALLED>Constance Smedley Armfield</SOCALLED>).</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></PAUTHORSHIP></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (16 November 1922): 745" DBREF="54246">(16 November 1922): 745</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>It is dedicated to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the Midland cousins, Hugh, Roger, Peggy, Celia.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Animal-Book prelims" DBREF="66206">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="LITERARY">This contains eight <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE> reminiscent in their titles of <NAME>Rudyard Kipling</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Just So Stories</TITLE>:</PINFLUENCESHER> <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">How the Horse Looked Ahead</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">How the Swallows Learned the Song</TITLE>, and so on. In the latter, a nestful of <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>young swallows</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> have been taught by their parents a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SONG">song</TGENRE> beginning <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">More and more refreshment / Is each swallow&apos;s need,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Animal-Book 55" DBREF="66206">55</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> but have come to believe it is their own composition, and is necessary instruction to the parent birds. In time they invent (as they believe) verses about flying, and finally, just in time, all the young ones, unable to learn from their elders, learn from their peers a verse about <TTHEMETOPIC>migration</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>The First Greenleaf Theatre; the Cotswold Players</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE">When CS first returned to dramatic work after her marriage it was as a collaborator on <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">animated tableaux</TGENRE> illustrating a <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLITICALWRITING">political version</TGENRE> of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC" REND="normal">Mary had a Little Lamb</TITLE> (chosen for its connection with the woollen industry)</QUOTE> in the <PLACE><REGION REG="Cotswolds">Cotswold</REGION> town of <SETTLEMENT>Minchinhampton</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 199" DBREF="106055">199</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">Next came the Armfields&apos; historical <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED"><TGENRE GENRENAME="PAGEANT">Pageant</TGENRE> of <TTHEMETOPIC>Progress</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, designed to further the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Liberal Party">Liberal</ORGNAME> cause in an election campaign.</PMOTIVES></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="SOCIALCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="PERIOD" CHRONCOLUMN1="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS1" RELEVANCE1="DECADE1"><DATESTRUCT CERTAINTY="C" VALUE="1911-07-"><SEASON VALUE="07" CERTAINTY="C">Summer</SEASON> <YEAR VALUE="1911">1911</YEAR></DATESTRUCT><CHRONPROSE>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED"><TGENRE GENRENAME="PAGEANT">Pageant</TGENRE> of Progress</TITLE> was first put on by CS and her <NAME STANDARD="Armfield, Maxwell">husband</NAME> in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Fromehall Park</PLACENAME>, <SETTLEMENT>Stroud</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (then a <SOCALLED>field</SOCALLED>, now a rugby club).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cotswold Players" DBREF="67505"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>One thousand three hundred people participated. It was designed to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">completely preoccupied with events as they affected the people&apos;s progress,</QUOTE> and to strike a positive note <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[a]t a time of great depression and unrest,</QUOTE> but neither to sentimentalize the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>common people</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> nor to depict the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>upper class</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> unfavourably as a group, since individual members of it were shown as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>helpers and wise counsellors</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> throughout.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 203" DBREF="106055">203</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PPERFORMANCE>It had a single rehearsal and three performances <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">in a field <PLACE>[<PLACENAME>Fromehall Park</PLACENAME>] at <SETTLEMENT>Stroud</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>,</QUOTE> drawing crowds of more than 5,000 on the first day and over 9,000 on the last. <PCIRCULATION>Though some of the expensive grandstand seats were empty, <PPRICE>the five-shilling and half-a-crown seats on grassy banks were packed:</PPRICE> some villages attended en masse.</PCIRCULATION> So many coins were handed in that gatekeepers had difficulty carrying them all.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 206" DBREF="106055">206</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cotswold Players" DBREF="67505"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERFORMANCE></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The action began with the <TTHEMETOPIC>Druids</TTHEMETOPIC> (earlier groups like ancient Britons having been rejected because of the scanty clothing deemed necessary for the parts), and proceeded past <TTHEMETOPIC>Doomsday book</TTHEMETOPIC>, the <TTHEMETOPIC><TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="abolition of slavery">abolition</TMOTIF> of slavery (that is serfdom)</TTHEMETOPIC>, the <TOPIC>English Civil War</TOPIC>, the <TOPIC>Corn Law</TOPIC> riots, up to the present day. <PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES">CS planned the details of the story with <NAME STANDARD="Gwynne-Evans, Frank">Frank Gwynne Evans</NAME>, to whom she handed over the actual writing (in verse) and whose name alone appeared on the programme.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 201-4, 207" DBREF="106055">201-4, 207</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PAUTHORSHIP></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">Though Liberals welcomed the pageant, it was widely condemned by the <SOCALLED>County</SOCALLED> or local landowners as socialistic.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 203, 206" DBREF="106055">203, 206</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> But the driver who took the Armfields home at the end of the last day said: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Never such a sight did I think to see. Two thousand years unrolled and all the people of these parts alive again.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 206" DBREF="106055">206</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><NAME>William Dean Howells</NAME>, who travelled from Wales to see the pageant, wrote <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a charming appreciation</QUOTE> which was published in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">North American Review</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 206-7" DBREF="106055">206-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL">It was to be nearly six decades before <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Pageant of the People</TITLE> (which came only a few years after<NAME>Cicely Hamilton</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Pageant of Great Women</TITLE>)</PINFLUENCESHER> <RSHEINFLUENCED>was followed by <NAME>Ann Jellicoe</NAME>&apos;s pageants or large-scale <TGENRE GENRENAME="PAGEANT">community plays</TGENRE>.</RSHEINFLUENCED></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Pageant of the People, The">Pageant of the People</TITLE> set CS to writing <TGENRE GENRENAME="ONEACTPLAY">one-act plays</TGENRE> that would spread related ideas about the <TTHEMETOPIC>need for social progress</TTHEMETOPIC>:</PMOTIVES> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT">one about the <TTHEMETOPIC>political battle in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Stroud</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> to found a Free Library</TTHEMETOPIC> there,</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">and another about the feuds in medieval <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Florence</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, which CS perceived to have been a very similar community.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> She found <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Play-writing was quite a difficult art to resume</QUOTE> after years away from it, but she was driven by explicitly feminist motives, since she felt that many local women found <TTHEMETOPIC>printed political discourse</TTHEMETOPIC> hard to decode.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 208" DBREF="106055">208</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In rural <PLACE><REGION>Gloucestershire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> talk was the medium of political opinion, and local people who might be baffled by such issues as women going out to work in offices nevertheless understood and held opinions on issues of <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">domestic violence</TMOTIF> and <TTHEMETOPIC>management of household money</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 209" DBREF="106055">209</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Journalism</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Soon after arriving in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, CS was researching in the <ORGNAME STANDARD="New York Public Library">New York Public Library</ORGNAME> and writing <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">articles</TGENRE> on <TTHEMETOPIC>folklore</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>arts and crafts</TTHEMETOPIC> for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Christian Science Monitor, The">Christian Science Monitor</TITLE> and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Woman&apos;s Magazine</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 229-230" DBREF="106055">229-230</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Greenleaf Theatre</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING>Plays</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Dramatic writings by CS and her husband in the USA began with the <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">five-act</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED"><TCHARACTERNAME>Miriam</TCHARACTERNAME>, Sister of Moses</TITLE>, about the <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC" REG="Bible" REND="normal">Old Testament</TITLE> character who was <TTHEMETOPIC>healed of leprosy</TTHEMETOPIC>. They had been working on this for some years but could not envisage its being performed. <PPERFORMANCE>It was finally given a summer performance at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Greek Theatre,, Berkeley">Greek Theatre</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Berkeley</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="California"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>,</PPERFORMANCE> <PARCHIVALLOCATION>and the <ORGNAME STANDARD="New York Public Library">New York Public Library</ORGNAME> holds photographs of <NAME>Ruth St Denis</NAME> in this performance.</PARCHIVALLOCATION> CS also wrote for students at <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of California at Berkeley">Berkeley</ORGNAME> <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The King&apos;s Progress</TITLE>, a kind of <TGENRE GENRENAME="PAGEANT">pageant</TGENRE> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">featuring a visit of the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>boy king</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <NAME STANDARD="Edward VI, King">Edward VI</NAME> to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Southampton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Hampshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> For once CS was not involved in the production of her own work.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 245-6" DBREF="106055">245-6</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATERANGE CERTAINTY="ROUGHLYDATED" FROM="1922--" TO="1925--" EXACT="BOTH">Between 1922 and 1925</DATERANGE><CHRONPROSE>CS published a series of <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Greenleaf Rhythmic <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">Plays</TGENRE></TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>CS had moved smoothly from writing <TGENRE GENRENAME="ONEACTPLAY">one-act plays</TGENRE> for the <ORGNAME>Cotswold Players</ORGNAME> to writing them for the first, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="London">Chelsea</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, incarnation of the Greenleaf Players. She wrote a number of plays for performance by the <ORGNAME>Greenleaf Theatre</ORGNAME> in two series, <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Greenleaf Rhythmic Plays</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Greenleaf Theatre Plays</TITLE>. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Belle and Beau</TITLE> appeared in print in 1922. So too did <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Curious Herbal, The">The Curious Herbal: telling of Mrs. <NAME STANDARD="Blackwell, Elizabeth,, 1707 - 1758">Elizabeth Blackwell</NAME>&apos;s visit to the Old Chelsea Herb Garden in 1732</TITLE>, which, with <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Minstrel</TITLE>, made up the first performance at their Greenleaf Studio in Chelsea, <PEDITIONS>and which was re-issued by <ORGNAME>Samuel French</ORGNAME> in 1930 with a different subtitle in the first series of <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Greenleaf Theatre Plays</TITLE>, <PPRICE>price one shilling</PPRICE>.</PEDITIONS> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gilded Wreath: a Modern Caricature in one act</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fortunate Shepherds: a Cotswold Pastoral</TITLE> were published in 1925 and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oranges and Beans: a Californian Rhapsody in one act</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Pierrot&apos;s Welcome: a Moonlight Pastoral in one act</TITLE> in 1930. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodelian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 218, 222" DBREF="106055">218, 222</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="IMITATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE"><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="VERSIFICATION"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WORKINGCLASS"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Fortunate Shepherds: a Cotswold Pastoral, The">The Fortunate Shepherds </TITLE> (which brings <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>hill shepherds</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> into contact with <PLACE><REGION>Forest of Dean</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>miners</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>)</TSETTINGPLACE> uses the twelve verse-metres used by <NAME STANDARD="Spenser, Edmund">Spenser</NAME> in his <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Shepheardes Calender, The">Shepheards&apos; Calendar</TITLE>.</TTECHNIQUES></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P><P>In <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Curious Herbal</TITLE> CS dramatises the genesis of the similarly-titled work by the <TTHEMETOPIC>eighteenth-century illustrator and herbalist <NAME STANDARD="Blackwell, Elizabeth,, 1707 - 1758">Elizabeth Blackwell</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>. While her husband was in debtors&apos; prison, Blackwell began visiting the <TTHEMETOPIC>botanical gardens in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="London">Chelsea</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC> to work on the book which she published in 1737-9 as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Curious Herbal, containing five hundred cuts, of the most useful plants, which are now used, in the practice of physick</TITLE>, with her own <SOCALLED>cuts</SOCALLED> or engravings on copper.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 216, 222" DBREF="106055">216, 222</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Blackwell" DBREF="29268">under Blackwell</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Smedley&apos;s <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Blackwell, Elizabeth">Mrs Blackwell</TCHARACTERNAME>, dressed in many-coloured <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">prodigious flowered skirts,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Herbal 7" DBREF="67246">7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> is fixated on making money for her imprisoned husband, and is properly, even excessively humble before two authoritative men in succession: <TCHARACTERNAME>Doctor Rand</TCHARACTERNAME> of the herb garden and <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Miller, Philip"><NAME>Philip Miller</NAME></TCHARACTERNAME> of the gardens proper, author of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gardeners and Florists Dictionary</TITLE>, 1724. These, misogynists both, bar her from entrance until she firstly threatens self-harm with a trowel, and secondly reveals that her husband was the printer of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="The Gardeners and Florists Dictionary">The Gardeners Dictionary</TITLE>. By these questionable means she gets her way.</P><P><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="VERSIFICATION">Smedley wrote this play and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Gilded Wreath: a Modern Caricature in one act, The">The Gilded Wreath</TITLE> in verse, and divided them into movements parallelling those of a musical composition.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 216, 222" DBREF="106055">216, 222</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTECHNIQUES></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RSHEINFLUENCED>Smedley says that <NAME>Geoffrey Whitworth</NAME> first conceived of the project which became his influential <ORGNAME>British Drama League</ORGNAME> after a performance of her <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Pierrot&apos;s Welcome: a Moonlight Pastoral in one act">Pierrot&apos;s Welcome</TITLE> enabled him to see <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the possibility of drama that would be worth doing, even by inexperienced performers.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 211" DBREF="106055">211</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSHEINFLUENCED> (The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> seems to attribute the inspiration for the League&mdash;which in 1972 became the <ORGNAME STANDARD="British Drama League">British Theatre Association</ORGNAME>&mdash;to a different community production.)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Whitworth" DBREF="29268">under Whitworth</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Greenleaf Theatre Elements</TITLE></HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Along with her series of plays CS issued a series of three <TGENRE GENRENAME="TEXTBOOK">textbooks</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Greenleaf Theatre Elements</TITLE>, 1924&#150;6, or <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Action</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Speech</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Production</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> These embodied <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a synopsis of <QUOTE DIRECT="N">the <TGENRE GENRENAME="SPEECH">lectures</TGENRE>, directors&apos; courses, and classes</QUOTE></QUOTE> that she and her husband had given in the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE> at <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">various universities, colleges, community theaters and workshops, and women&apos;s clubs.</QUOTE> <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>She provided <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">detailed diagrammatic notations</QUOTE> for the gestures her husband designed.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 6" DBREF="65965" QTDIN="QTDINYES">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>In July 1922 CS published an <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY"><TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">article</TGENRE></TGENRE> about the <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME>Greenleaf Theatre</ORGNAME> ventures</TTHEMETOPIC> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The English Review</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 6n5" DBREF="65965">6n5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Children&apos;s Books</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66225" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Wonder Tales of the World, 1920"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>1920</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES"><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>CS used her married name of <SOCALLED>Constance Armfield</SOCALLED> to publish at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE> a collection of <TGENRE GENRENAME="LEGENDFOLKTALE">folk-tales</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">told for children</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Wonder Tales of the World</TITLE>, partnered with illustrations by her husband, <NAME>Maxwell Armfield</NAME>.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></PAUTHORSHIP></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>This began as a <TGENRE GENRENAME="JOURNALISM">series of articles</TGENRE> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Christian Science Monitor</TITLE> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS DISPLACEMENT="DISPLACEMENTYES">while CS was living with her husband in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 17" DBREF="65965">17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> <PARCHIVALLOCATION><PDEDICATION>The <ORGNAME>UCLA</ORGNAME> copy of the resulting book, digitized and available through <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="OCLC WorldCat">OCLC</TITLE>, is a presentation copy inscribed <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">To our dear Father and Mother. This wonder-book&mdash;for Christmastime&mdash;from their eternal children, Connie and Max.</QUOTE></PDEDICATION></PARCHIVALLOCATION> <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><NAME STANDARD="Armfield, Maxwell">Armfield</NAME>&apos;s visual styles range from soaring birds on the cover to a statuesque crinolined figure as frontispiece.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">Each of these <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">less-known stories</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Timbuktu prelims" DBREF="65885">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> comes from a different country, the first two being from <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">America</GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><AREA REG="Arabian Peninsula">Arabia</AREA></PLACE>. Also represented are <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Scotland</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Wales</GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><GEOG>Ireland</GEOG></PLACE>, and so are <PLACE><GEOG>Norway</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Bulgaria</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Greece</GEOG></PLACE> (<TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Prince and the Eagle</TITLE>), <PLACE><GEOG>Hungary</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Serbia</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>India</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Japan</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Korea</GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><GEOG>New Zealand</GEOG></PLACE> (<TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Boys Who Left Trouble Behind</TITLE>).</TSETTINGPLACE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="65885" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Tales from Timbuktu, 1923"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1923-11-15" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid November 1923</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES"><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>CS (using her birth name) and her husband, <NAME>Maxwell Armfield</NAME> (as illustrator), returned to the formula of their <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Wonder Tales of the World</TITLE> for another collection of <TGENRE GENRENAME="LEGENDFOLKTALE">folk stories</TGENRE><TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE"> for children</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Tales from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Timbuktu</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Mali"></GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE></TITLE>.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></PAUTHORSHIP></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (15 November 1923): 762" DBREF="54246">(15 November 1923): 762</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Like its predecessor, this was published in the USA but not in England. CS dated her foreword 20 July 1923 from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Ringwood</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Hampshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (presumably meaning <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Mockbeggar</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Hampshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, just a couple of miles away from Ringwood, which was Maxwell Armfield&apos;s birthplace).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Timbuktu v" DBREF="65885">v</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Armfield" DBREF="29268">under Armfield</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The book is dedicated <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">With Our Love To Di.</QUOTE> CS&apos;s introductory poem, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Town of Timbuktu</TITLE>, is addressed to <SOCALLED>G. A. W.</SOCALLED><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Timbuktu prelims, xi" DBREF="65885">prelims, xi</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="FEMALE">A short bibliography (which includes translated texts) lists <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Golden Chersonese and the Way Thither, The">The Golden Chersonese</TITLE> by <NAME>Isabella Bird</NAME> (under her married name of <SOCALLED>Bishop</SOCALLED>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Timbuktu 180" DBREF="65885">180</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TTONESTYLE>A <TGENRE GENRENAME="PREFATORYPIECE">prefatory <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poem</TGENRE></TGENRE> introduces <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Timbuktu</SETTLEMENT> (now in <GEOG REG="Mali">Mali</GEOG>)<AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>, the lost centre of African culture (seat of one of the world&apos;s most famous libraries), in a light-hearted, romantic tone:</TTONESTYLE></TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Oh the far-fetched so-they-sayness of the town of Timbuktu! / the have-we-heard-arightness of the things its people do; / The wonders known to wandering men . . . .</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Timbuktu xi" DBREF="65885">xi</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="DICTION"><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="IMITATION">The prose style has an orientalizing excess which relates it to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Arabian Nights">The Arabian Nights</TITLE>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></TTECHNIQUES> The protagonist of the frame story&mdash;a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">Prince of Persia, already unimaginably rich in treasures</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, who decides to travel to Timbuktu in the hope that its <TTHEMETOPIC>world-famous market</TTHEMETOPIC> will offer his something new to desire&mdash;is introduced with an elaborate account of his splendour: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The eyes on his peacocks&apos; tails were large as saucers and blue as lapis; the tusks of his elephants made fresh-fallen snow look yellow; in his menagerie Hippogriffs and Unicorns were common; and when it came to jewels, one had to put on three pairs of horn spectacles at the entrance of the corridor leading to the treasure. Even then few escaped being blinded.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Timbuktu 3" DBREF="65885">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></QUOTE> The <TTHEMETOPIC>rich goods and the cosmopolitan crowds</TTHEMETOPIC> at the market of Timbuktu banish his <TTHEMETOPIC>disease of over-richness</TTHEMETOPIC>, but only for a while. When it returns, his <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Vizier</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> proposes a tale-market, where all <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">whom your Highness&apos;s visit has benefited</QUOTE> shall relate a story. In fact each tells two stories: one about the benefit received, and another which is traditional in his or her own country or region. <TVOICENARRATION>First come those from Africa: the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Kaffir porter</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, the <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Democratic Republic of the Congo" REG="Congo">Congo</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE> <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>water-carrier</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Hausa drummer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Calabar</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Nigeria" REG="Nigeria"></GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>.</TVOICENARRATION> The porter has escaped a punishment because of the prince&apos;s arrival; the water-carrier has learned a new method of keeping his water cool; the drummer, who was on the run from a king who wanted to blind him and set him to work at a sacred temple, has found a new and safe place to exercise his art. Each of these tells a <TGENRE GENRENAME="FABLE">fable</TGENRE> of <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>talking animals</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. Then come those from <PLACE><AREA>Asia</AREA></PLACE>, from the little <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Korean girl</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> to the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Cambodian dancer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Coptic clerk</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, with an outlier to close the collection, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Chilean jewel merchant. The Prince returns home transformed, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">no longer a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">delicate youth, but a magnificently vigorous young man</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>,</QUOTE></TCHARACTERTYPEROLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Timbuktu 176" DBREF="65885">176</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> with two of the story-tellers to accompany him. At home he hears his mother relate the final story, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Feasts of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Shiraz</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Iran" REG="Persia"></GEOG></PLACE></TITLE>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="PARABLE">parable</TGENRE> designed to demonstrate that a <TTHEMETOPIC>simple dinner of rice and vegetables is better than luxurious banquets</TTHEMETOPIC>. The Vizier, who still cares about riches, is left to transport his material purchases home as best he may.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES">In 1927 there appeared from <ORGNAME>Oxford University Press</ORGNAME> another Smedley-Armfield collection of tales for children, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Blue Bus Route: Being the Amazing Adventures of Kenneth and Barbara in the <TTHEMETOPIC>Folk Song</TTHEMETOPIC> World</TITLE>. It was dedicated by permission to the <ORGNAME STANDARD="English Folk Dance Society">English Folk-Dance Society</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (20 October 1927): 743" DBREF="54246">(20 October 1927): 743</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 251" DBREF="106055">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PAUTHORSHIP></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE">Here CS <TGENRE GENRENAME="ADAPTATION">re-told</TGENRE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the stories of <NAME>Cecil Sharp</NAME>&apos;s folk-songs.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 251" DBREF="106055">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1940</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY>The last book that CS published was <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Peter in Sweden</TITLE>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">novel for children</TGENRE> in which a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">young English boy</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, sent to stay with <PLACE><GEOG REG="Sweden">Swedish</GEOG></PLACE> relations, learns how it feels to be a foreigner.</PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY></TSETTINGPLACE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Novels</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Unholy Experiment</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66026" PLACEHOLDER="CS, The Unholy Experiment, 1924"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1924-06-16" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid June 1924</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">A couple of years after her return from <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">America</GEOG></PLACE>, CS set a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> there: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Unholy Experiment</TITLE>, which draws on but radically alters some of her own experience. <PDEDICATION>She dedicated it to her <NAME STANDARD="Smedley, William Thomas">father</NAME>.</PDEDICATION></TSETTINGPLACE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (12 June 1924): 364" DBREF="54246">(12 June 1924): 364</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 248-9" DBREF="106055">248-9</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy, prelims" DBREF="66027">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>The title derives, via other allusions, from <NAME>William Penn</NAME>&apos;s name for his Quaker colony of <PLACE><REGION>Pennsylvania</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>: the holy experiment.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>CS defined the theme of this novel as the <TTHEMETOPIC>gulf between English and American attitudes to the law</TTHEMETOPIC>. Law, she wrote, was respected in England but seen in the USA as merely a convenience or an impediment to personal goals. Excited by American independence of the law, she also felt that this, like English dependence on it, was less than satisfactory.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 248" DBREF="106055">248</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT">Like Smedley but in very different circumstances, her heroine, <TCHARACTERNAME>Lucia Craven</TCHARACTERNAME>, travels from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE> via <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Chicago</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Illinois"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><REGION>Kansas</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Albuquerque</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New Mexico"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, and the <PLACE><REGION>Grand Canyon</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><REGION>California</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, and records impressions not unlike those which a review perceived in <NAME>Maxwell Armfield</NAME>&apos;s London exhibition of paintings of America: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">loneliness and grandeur,</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">monumental primitiveness</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bowe, Constance and Maxwell, 6" DBREF="65965" QTDIN="QTDINYES">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> Lucia, however (a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">successful novelist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>), is travelling not to an exciting country she wishes to be part of, but because her husband, Ronnie (a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>painter</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>), <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">has left her for an American woman</TMOTIF> (a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>midwesterner who has charmed him to coveting the culture</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> he has to impart). He wants a <TMOTIF>divorce</TMOTIF>, while Lucia thinks of <TTHEMETOPIC>marriage as an indissoluble contract</TTHEMETOPIC>. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Here was a great nature, scarred and tortured, but not trivially distraught.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 4" DBREF="66027">4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She wishes to see the native land of her rival. Unlike Maxwell Armfield, Lucia hates New York. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The narrow island seethed with life of such instancy and speed that the velocity became a nightmare.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 4" DBREF="66027">4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She cannot connect with Americans, whom she sees as insulated by their <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">invulnerable common sense.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 7" DBREF="66027">7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Indeed, the cross-purposes between people (not always of different nationalities) make a refrain in this book. On the train Lucia meets an American with whom she can connect, <TCHARACTERNAME>Whitman Udell</TCHARACTERNAME>, though each at first sees the other as a type. She guesses him to be from the west: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I hope I shall meet a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>real Westerner</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 23" DBREF="66027">23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He feels she approaches him <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">as if he were some foreign animal with whom reserve was unnecessary,</QUOTE> and guesses her to be English because of her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">certain condescension to foreigners.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 24" DBREF="66027">24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Nevertheless rapport springs up between them; he is protective with her as he is not usually with women. The mutual attaction survives her discovery that Udell is a friend of <TCHARACTERNAME>Davis Hedges</TCHARACTERNAME>, the man whose wife has deserted him for Lucia&apos;s husband.</P><P>Hedges, with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a sales-talk . . . selling the most superb, sensational, remarkable scenic experience,</QUOTE> and a torrent of facts and statistics,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 77" DBREF="66027">77</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> sends Lucia and Udell to the <PLACE><REGION>Grand Canyon</REGION></PLACE>, and the experience of it, the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">silence of utter desolation well[ing] up from its depths</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 92-3" DBREF="66027">92-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> propels them by contrast into a <TTHEMETOPIC>shared erotic moment</TTHEMETOPIC>&mdash;which is shattered by the intrusion of Lucia&apos;s ordinary life when they reach the hotel on the canyon&apos;s rim. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Why, it&apos;s Mrs. Craven! Why, Lucia Craven, what are you doing here?</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 101" DBREF="66027">101</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>After this things become more complicated, as both Lucia and Whitman Udell begin to meet friends or acquaintances of the other: she learns that he is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>magazine editor</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, at ease in her own world, and also that he has been twice married. In California she returns to her hotel room to find a man in it: her husband, Ronnie, who has ended his affair and strolled back into her life, asking: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Can&apos;t you just take me on again, as if it had been a rotten dream</QUOTE>?<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 153" DBREF="66027">153</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">Lucia, who has been thinking of marriage as a contract which he has illegally broken, now finds that he needs it to be repaired so that he can inherit a beloved family estate, Greenfields.</TMOTIF> But the choice apparently facing Lucia, between a <TTHEMETOPIC>marriage of convenience and mutual understanding</TTHEMETOPIC> on one hand, and challenge and passion on the other, becomes more complicated in turn as the <TTHEMETOPIC>anger and jealousy</TTHEMETOPIC> between her and Ronnie signal the strength of their tie. She parts from Udell with anger and <TMOTIF>violence</TMOTIF>, and retraces with Ronnie the train journey which again provides emotional response to the natural world and growing human closeness. Ronnie&apos;s aesthetic eye makes even the newness of New York pleasing.</P><P>Late in the book comes a turn back to <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satire</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="EPISTOLARY">in a series of letters from minor characters.</TGENRE> American friends of Lucia&apos;s, one resident in London, reduce profound experience to gossip. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I had thought her a little <EMPH>English</EMPH> when I met her in London, but she came out of her shell, and was as buoyant and sparkling as a girl!</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 284" DBREF="66027">284</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Now&mdash;well, [the Cravens&apos; marriage] it&apos;s jog-trot. It&apos;s like riding behind high steppers who&apos;ve had a fall.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 289" DBREF="66027">289</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Whitman Udell writes about embarking on his third mariage, to (in someone else&apos;s words) <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the cutest little thing you ever saw</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 285" DBREF="66027">285</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> but in his own <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an enthusiastic member of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="American Indian Defense Association">Indian Defense Association</ORGNAME> </QUOTE> who, despite her appearance, might contemplate a political career.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 298" DBREF="66027">298</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>The <ORGNAME>American Indian Defense Association</ORGNAME>, founded only in 1923, set out to reverse the existing policy of suppression of native cultures as <SOCALLED>uncivilized</SOCALLED>.</P></SCHOLARNOTE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Emmeline Hedges</TCHARACTERNAME>, now Emmeline Hedges Porter, writes about her amibitions for a <TTHEMETOPIC>movie career for her five-year-old daugher</TTHEMETOPIC> Rosabell, who is small-built enough to stay five, professionally, for years. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I wish you could see the way she can round her eyes and put such a childish, innocent look in them.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 307" DBREF="66027">307</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> CS later wrote that she felt her portrait of a midwestern woman with sincere, if vague <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">yearnings for artistic expression,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 248" DBREF="106055">248</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> whose <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">highest and deepest values</QUOTE> dissolve at the prospect of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">commercial success or standardized publicity,</QUOTE> was lifelike and accurate.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 249" DBREF="106055">249</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Last of all comes a letter from Lucia <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">to the author and artist of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Holy Experiment</TITLE></QUOTE>&mdash;that is, to the actual <NAME>Violet Oakley</NAME> (American artist, feminist, and socialist). Oakley privately printed in 1922, with text in many languages, a book reproducing her series of mural paintings for the Pennsylvania state capitol: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Holy Experiment, The">The Holy Experiment. A Message to the World from Pennsylvania</TITLE>. She gets several admiring pages in Smedley&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Crusaders</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 247-8" DBREF="106055">247-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In her letter closing the novel Lucia does not mention her recently born <SOCALLED>Son and Heir</SOCALLED>. She recalls the <TTHEMETOPIC>idealism with which <PLACE><REGION>Pennsylvania</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE> was founded</TTHEMETOPIC>; she wonders about the <TTHEMETOPIC>modern, materialistic, militaristic <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">United States</GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>; she sets out what she, as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an idealist, perhaps a modernist,</QUOTE> admires about the USA,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 315" DBREF="66027">315</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and also what her time there has taught her: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Acceptance of the things that come one&apos;s way, making the best out of them, refusing to look back and mourn, giving up vain ideals, beholding illusions as illusions.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Unholy 316" DBREF="66027">316</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">Smedley says she aimed to show her English characters from an American standpoint, not to endorse them (and particularly not to endorse Lucia&apos;s decision to return to England, which she saw as a mistake).</PMOTIVES> A few years later she would have reversed her protagonist&apos;s decision. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">She was surprised when American readers responded with animosity to her portrait of Emmeline Hedges, accusing her of British prejudice. </RRESPONSES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 248-9" DBREF="106055">248-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Justice Walk</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66226" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Justice Walk, 1924"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1924-11-13" CERTAINTY="BY">By late 1924</DATE><CHRONPROSE>CS&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="EPISTOLARY">epistolary</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Justice Walk</TITLE>, published with <ORGNAME STANDARD="George Allen and Unwin">G. Allen and Unwin</ORGNAME> this year but begun in 1915 during the <TOPIC STANDARD="World War One">Great War</TOPIC>, was designed as an anti-war, pro-art <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLEMIC">polemic</TGENRE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (13 November 1924): 726" DBREF="54246">(13 November 1924): 726</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 10" DBREF="66006">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><NAME STANDARD="Unwin, Sir Stanley">Stanley Unwin</NAME>&apos;s <NAME STANDARD="Unwin, Alice Mary">wife</NAME> read the manuscript and told her husband that he had got to publish the novel for the sake of its ideas. (Unwin was an internationally-minded pacifist.) <PCONTRACT>The firm signed a contract at once for both this and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Redwing</TITLE>, but they then felt <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Justice Walk</TITLE> was too outrageous to publish, more controversial even than the anti-imperialist <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Redwing</TITLE>. It took nearly a decade before it was issued.</PCONTRACT><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 224-5" DBREF="106055">224-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PDEDICATION>CS dedicated the book to her <NAME STANDARD="Armfield, Maxwell">husband</NAME>.</PDEDICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION>The protagonist and letter-writer, <TCHARACTERNAME>Samuel Pumphrey</TCHARACTERNAME>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 122" DBREF="66226">122</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE"><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Friends">Quaker</ORGNAME> clerk, puritan, provincial and utterly inartistic,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 224" DBREF="106055">224</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> as well as initially self-righteous</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</TVOICENARRATION> <TPLOT>Before the story begins he was saving money to marry his beloved Margaret and bring her to share the family home in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Painswick</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>&mdash;saving slowly since he supports his <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>two sisters, who are delicate, nervous, and unqualified</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> (because his beliefs about women have made him refuse them permission to train for paid work). After twenty-five years with a firm in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Gloucester</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, he has disgraced himself through prejudice against a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>new, younger employee for being smartly dressed and keen on amateur theatricals</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. Samuel got this man fired on suspicion of pilfering cash, then, months later, found the missing money in a drawer where he himself had carelessly forgotten it. He got the other man reinstated but could not face staying on himself.</TPLOT> So here he is in London, in a worse-paid job, more remote than ever from being able to marry, <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">miserable, lonely, and disapproving</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> of everything. The novel charts his evolution from this low point, his redemption through art. CS said she wished here to recommend <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the need of <TTHEMETOPIC>Art as a redemptive force</TTHEMETOPIC> in life.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 224" DBREF="106055">224</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT">Samuel Pumphrey finds lodgings in the actual <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Justice Walk</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS>, <SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Chelsea">Chelsea</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. His landlord, <TCHARACTERNAME>Bertram Flower</TCHARACTERNAME>, turns out to be an actor: he has stumbled into an artists&apos; colony.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> <TCHARACTERIZATION>Very gradually he comes to accept, even admire, people he had fiercely disapproved of, particularly <TCHARACTERNAME>Johanna Hervey</TCHARACTERNAME>, his artist neighbour, who has left a respectable home and slept around, and wears bright strings of beads like a savage. Samuel finds her ghastly, vile, a mockery of the ideal of woman. Johanna, a personification of revolutionary spirit, is contrasted with Mary Bevell, who is housewifely and serves her artist husband. Samuel admires Mary, while Johanna looks forward to the day <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">when she ceases to humour, flatter, and nurse the pride of Man.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 110" DBREF="66226">110</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Mary is not quite what Samuel thinks: she has come from poverty and formerly worked as a model.</TCHARACTERIZATION></P><P>Then Johanna is found dead, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="suicide">believed to have poisoned herself</TMOTIF>. Her <TTHEMETOPIC>radicalism</TTHEMETOPIC> has made her and her art unpopular, and she <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of heroine">dies poor, sick, and alone</TMOTIF>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">leaving for posterity</TMOTIF> her <TTHEMETOPIC>idealism and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">uncompromising moral principles</QUOTE></TTHEMETOPIC><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 10" DBREF="66006">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She has made Samuel her executor. Her numerous wills, addressed to her family and various individuals (not legally valid but philosophically powerful), rail against the institutions of <TTHEMETOPIC>domesticity</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>militarism</TTHEMETOPIC>&mdash;which she sees as linked. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Do you beat the sword into the ploughshare? / Or do you hang the Christmas Tree with swords and drums?</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 101" DBREF="66226">101</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She thus links <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the <TTHEMETOPIC>subordination of women</TTHEMETOPIC>, and the <TTHEMETOPIC>vicious psychology of war</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE> The <TTHEMETOPIC>sentimentality of conventional women</TTHEMETOPIC> is implicated in men&apos;s eagerness to embrace war. Traditional women&apos;s arts <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">warm the hand that slays the Fellow-men,</QUOTE> whereas modern, revolutionary women&apos;s arts can create <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">firm and beautiful stitches of <TTHEMETOPIC>love for Humanity</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brockington 10" DBREF="66006" QTDIN="QTDINYES">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Johanna bequeathes to Samuel her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">hatred of Accumulations; / Of the ordure of Outgrown Personalities; / Of the excrement of Old Associations: / Of the miasma of Sentimentality.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 103" DBREF="66226">103</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> From beyond the grave she tells him: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Little man, you fear things about me which are not true, because you fear me as a woman.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 123" DBREF="66226">123</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">By now Samuel is changing. He likens Johanna to <NAME STANDARD="Blake, William">Blake</NAME>, whom she has quoted, though he has hitherto admired the balance and rationality of <NAME STANDARD="Addison, Joseph">Addison</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 136, 249" DBREF="66226">136, 249</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> His acquaintance with artists increases. He befriends two girls he calls the Turtles, who plan to write and produce plays to bring beauty into poor people&apos;s lives.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 199, 246-7" DBREF="66226">199, 246-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He even agrees to act with them, wearing a strange and brilliant costume&mdash;although he is baffled to find that they <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">have no notion of propriety at all.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 199" DBREF="66226">199</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He is promoted at work, and takes more calmly than one might expect the news that in his absence his sisters are making changes at home (cutting shrubs which shade the windows) and reminding him that the house is theirs, not his, under their father&apos;s will.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 123" DBREF="66226">209, 237, 243</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It turns out they are both <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="work for a living">earning money</TMOTIF>, and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">desire complete independence.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 244" DBREF="66226">244</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> By the time he has at last distributed Johanna&apos;s bequests, he feels <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">nothing but the desire to atone for my pride, my fear, my cowardice, my hardness to both dead and living.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 287" DBREF="66226">287</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He confides to Margaret: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Since I have come among these people everything I thought was solid is at sea. . . . I have a strange feeling that my attitude to women is not, in truth, respectful. It is that of a tyrant who is for ever judging and dictating to inferiors.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 291-2" DBREF="66226">291-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He now fears the artists despise and reject him; he also fears that Primula, the junior Turtle, is about to be seduced by <TCHARACTERNAME>Gervase Bathurst</TCHARACTERNAME>. But Gervase marries Primula, and Samuel is forgiven at the <TCHARACTERNAME>wedding feast</TCHARACTERNAME>. By the end he and Margaret are also about to marry. The book&apos;s last words are <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Justice in all, yes, and Mercy too.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Justice 320" DBREF="66226">320</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">This work was reviewed by <NAME>Mary Webb</NAME> for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Bookman, The">Bookman</TITLE> in January 1925 together with <NAME>Ethel Sidgwick</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Laura: A Cautionary Story</TITLE> and <NAME>V. H. Friedlaender</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Colour of Youth</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mary Webb, Neglected Genius" DBREF="66227"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> According to Smedley herself, the book was received as something quite different from what she had written. Though a few voices attacked it, most welcomed <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a book of exquisite fragrance, in the manner of <NAME>Jane Austen</NAME>.</QUOTE> The <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">advanced views, the passionate chastising of <TTHEMETOPIC>puritanism</TTHEMETOPIC> . . . the ruthless analysis of war</QUOTE> and of a <TTHEMETOPIC>war-mentality peace</TTHEMETOPIC>, all passed the commentators by. <RSELFDESCRIPTION>A few years after publishing this novel CS still trusted that it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">will one day be read and understood.</QUOTE></RSELFDESCRIPTION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 225" DBREF="106055">225</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Of her further <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Walls</TITLE> appeared in 1929, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Woman in the Wilderness</TITLE> in 1930, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Magnolia Lady</TITLE> in 1932.</P><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Memoir</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106055" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Crusaders1929"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1929-01-28" CERTAINTY="BY">By late January 1929</DATE><CHRONPROSE>CS published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">volume of reminiscence</TGENRE> which she entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Crusaders</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (24 January 1929): 55" DBREF="54246">(24 January 1929): 55</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Life,</QUOTE> she wrote here, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">is a perpetual crusade.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 1-2" DBREF="106055">1-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PATTITUDES>She had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">had an irresistible desire to crystallize every phase in the form of some sort of story for grown-ups or children,</QUOTE> but the experiences had continued to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">more interesting to me than their literary expression.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 2" DBREF="106055">2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> She writes vividly about her <TTHEMETOPIC>early life in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Birmingham</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Warwickshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>, her delight at entering <TTHEMETOPIC>literary, artistic, and progressive circles in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>, and some of her <TTHEMETOPIC>writings and their reception</TTHEMETOPIC> (not without a few notes of self-congratulation). She goes into detail about her leadership in the <TTHEMETOPIC>campaign for the establishment of the international network of <ORGNAME STANDARD="International Association of Lyceum Clubs" REG="London Lyceum International Club">Lyceum Clubs</ORGNAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, and all their multifarious activities. She particularly praises the <TTHEMETOPIC>inspirational contribution of <NAME STANDARD="Balfour, Frances">Lady Frances Balfour</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> and (among many exciting speakers) a <TTHEMETOPIC>talk given by <NAME>Ethel Snowden</NAME> and introduced by the normally shy and retiring <NAME>May Sinclair</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 71-3, 96-100" DBREF="106055">71-3, 96-100</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>CS eschews dates and does not always elucidate sequence. She vividly describes driving in a <TTHEMETOPIC>suffrage procession to the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Albert Hall</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>, sharing a carriage with <NAME STANDARD="Campbell, Beatrice Stella">Mrs Patrick Campbell</NAME> and her daughter <NAME>Stella Campbell</NAME>, through repeated <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">storm[s] of hoots, hisses and abuse</QUOTE> (a surprise for women of the theatre, whose metier removes them from <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the consciousness of feminine disabilities</QUOTE>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 144-6" DBREF="106055">144-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> But there were several important suffrage processions to the Albert Hall, and Smedley does not say which she means.</P><P>This book gives a stimulating account of the amazingly energetic <TTHEMETOPIC>theatrical activity undertaken and carried through by CS and her husband in rural, urban, and university communities in England and the USA</TTHEMETOPIC>. It closes on an account of the state and the activities of the <TTHEMETOPIC><ORGNAME STANDARD="International Association of Lyceum Clubs" REG="London Lyceum International Club">Lyceum Club</ORGNAME> in the later 1920s</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Crusaders 255-9" DBREF="106055">255-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">According to <NAME>Grace Brockington</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE>, this work <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">unabashedly promotes herself and her work, [and] captures her theatrical extravagance and warmth of character.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Grace Darling</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106056" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Grace Darling and her Times, 1932"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1932-10-27" CERTAINTY="BY">By late October 1932</DATE><CHRONPROSE>CS published a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biographical study</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Grace Darling and Her Times"><TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Grace Darling</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> and her Times</TITLE>, whose protagonist was famous as an ordinary woman capable at need of both physical strength and moral heroism.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (27 October 1932): 772" DBREF="54246">(27 October 1932): 772</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67405" PLACEHOLDER="CS, Grace Darling and her Islands, 1934"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1934-10-17" CERTAINTY="BY">By mid-October 1934</DATE><CHRONPROSE>CS&apos;s next book, covering much the same ground as her previous one but this time <TGENRE GENRENAME="YOUNGADULTWRITING">for younger readers</TGENRE>, was <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Grace Darling</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> and her Islands</TITLE>, published with the <ORGNAME>Religious Tract Society</ORGNAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC" DBREF="2052"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Dated from the <ORGNAME>Bodleian Library</ORGNAME> acquisition stamp.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>In a kind of dedication CS said that her book was written for the baby <NAME>Elizabeth Ann Collett</NAME>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">born in the first year of the Grace Darling League,</QUOTE> granddaughter of this year&apos;s Lord Mayor of London and Admiral of the Port of London, <NAME>Sir Charles Collett</NAME>. For fuller information she refers readers to her earlier Grace Darling book.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Darling 1934, 5" DBREF="67405">5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>CS claims more than once that her subject was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">our first national heroine,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Darling 1934, 7, 189" DBREF="67405">7, 189</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>and presents her in that role throughout&mdash;presents her implicitly as a child or adolescent rather than the young adult she was. Smedley begins: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">You have all heard of Grace Darling,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Darling 1934, 11" DBREF="67405">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and concludes on Grace&apos;s recently-discovered album, which opens with a poem about the sea and gives much attention to roses, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">as if the rose, our national emblem, was our heroine&apos;s favourite flower.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Darling 1934, 191" DBREF="67405">191</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She lovingly depicts the far more varied wildlife of Grace&apos;s home, <PLACE><PLACENAME>Brownsman</PLACENAME>, largest of the <REGION>Farne Islands</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, and vividly imagines the famous <TMOTIF>rescue</TMOTIF>, which begins with Grace summoned by her father after midnight to help secure their coble, or open boat (which takes three strong men to row it), against the exceptional gales and expected high tide. She comes out with her hair still in its curling rags: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">This was not a night for hair to be blowing across her eyes.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Darling 1934, 94" DBREF="67405">94</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> They secure other objects too, like the rabbits in their hutches, and as they go exhausted to bed at 4.45 a.m. it is not Mr Darling but Grace who looks out of the window and sees a huge vessel wrecked on the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Harcar</PLACENAME><REGION REG="Northumberland"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> reef.</P><P>Grace&apos;s <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="heroinism">heroism</TMOTIF> and physical strength are made acceptable in various ways: by her extreme modesty when fame comes to her, and by the female weakness of others. When Grace and her father need help to reverse their work and launch the coble they call on Mrs Darling. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Out she came, in her white frilled mobcap with her spectacles pushed up over the frill . . . . the bewildered old lady</QUOTE> whose parting words to her heroic child are <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Oh, Grace, if your faither is lost, I&apos;ll blame it all on you for this morning&apos;s work!</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Darling 1934, 99" DBREF="67405">99</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The first person rescued is a woman, helpless, almost unconscious.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smedley, Darling 1934, 101-2" DBREF="67405">101-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION><PAUTHORSHIP>Also in <DATE VALUE="1934-03-29">1934, on 29 March</DATE>, CS had <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">written to</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times">The Times</TITLE>, with her <NAME STANDARD="Armfield, Maxwell">husband</NAME> and six others, to propose that an <TTHEMETOPIC>oak-tree should be planted</TTHEMETOPIC> and conserved in every English sea-port in memory of Grace Darling. The letter-writers felt that Darling&apos;s story was too little or too inaccurately known.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Times Digital Archive 46715 (29 March 1934): 10" DBREF="24005">46715 (29 March 1934): 10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PAUTHORSHIP> In a follow-up letter of 9 April, CS (on her own) made the not wholly justifiable claim that Darling <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">was the first English woman other than a Queen to emerge from private life and to become nationally known, respected, and beloved.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Times Digital Archive 46723 (9 April 1934): 8" DBREF="24005">46723 (9 April 1934): 8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Recent Interest</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>During the last few years CS&apos;s works, long out of print, have begun to appear from the print-on-demand firm <ORGNAME>Nabu Press</ORGNAME> (a branch of <ORGNAME>BiblioBazaar</ORGNAME>). These titles (under the name of <SOCALLED>Anne Constance Smedley</SOCALLED>) are on sale at <ORGNAME>Tesco</ORGNAME> supermarkets and the website <XREF RESP="IMG" URL="http://buy.com/">Buy.com</XREF>. Comments on a blog concerned with publishing indicate that these reprints are likely to be unsatisfactory.<RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: the comments on the blog details problems with the publishing, but I could not find a specific reference to Smedley&apos;s titles in the blog. Is this okay as is? img to Kate and Mariana: I&apos;ve added to the prose a ref to  a website (maybe The website?) where these books are available. Hope this will do for a citation. OCLC doesn&apos;t list them, but if you Google her name and almost any of her titles you will find them.</RESEARCHNOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Shafranovich" DBREF="66045"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="ADFEMINAM"><PPERFORMANCE>In <DATE>March 2010</DATE> the <ORGNAME>Stroud Theatre Company</ORGNAME>, mindful of Smedley&apos;s local connection with <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Stroud</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (when she lived at nearby Minchinhampton), put on at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Everyman Theatre,, Cheltenham">Everyman Studio Theatre</ORGNAME> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Cheltenham</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Gloucestershire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> several performances of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Amazing and Preposterous Constance Smedley</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BBC Stroud Theatre Company" DBREF="66065"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERFORMANCE></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>BBC Gloucestershire, Stroud Theatre Company.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Brockington, Grace. A World Fellowship.</SOURCE><SOURCE>ODNB</SOURCE><SOURCE>Smedley, Constance. Tales from Timbuktu. 1923</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>